Proposed Responses to the ANSI Public Comments
==============================================
Josee Lajoie
josee@vnet.ibm.com
 
X3J16/96-0086
WG21/N0904
 
March 29th, 1996
 
This document incorporates all of the committee resolutions adopted
at the Santa Cruz meeting (March 1996).
 
Thanks to Steve Adamczyk, Pete Becker, Beman Dawes, Dave Dodgson, Bill
Gibbons, Philippe Le Mouel, Mike Miller, Nathan Myers, Tom Plum, Larry
Podmolik, Judy Ward and Rick Wilhelm for their help in providing
responses.
 
= = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = = =
 
  Upon Steve Clamage's request, I have put together a list of all the
  ANSI C++ public comments and have collected the proposed responses
  from the various WG chairs/issues list owners.
 
  I have either included the actual text of the comments in the list
  below (for the comments that were lists a small issues) or summarized
  the large comments in an attempt to keep the list short.  If you would
  like the see the entire text for a comment that has been summarized,
  Steve Rumsby's archive has a softcopy of all the ANSI public comments
  or you can let me know and I will email you what I have.
 
  Steve Clamage and Tom Plum will provide the official wording for the
  answers that will be mailed to the commenters.
 
  Each comment is numbered according to the registration number used by
  X3.  I had given temporary numbers to some of the comments at the
  Monterey meeting because X3 had not notified me of the comments
  numbers.  For these comments I have also indicated the comment's
  temporary number from the pre-Monterey meeting.
 
  You will notice that there are two kinds of comments in the list
  below:
  o official comments: those for which X3 received a signed hard copy
    version.
  o unofficial comments: those for which X3 only received a soft copy
    version.
  We decided in Monterey that we would answer both kinds of comments
  so all in all, this categorization does not make much difference to
  us.
 
  For some reason, X3 received many copies of some of the comments but
  assigned to each copy a different number.  For this reason, you will
  find some comments in the list below that have more than one number
    o comments 11 and 13 are the same comment
    o comments 14, 16 and unregistered comment 5 are the same comment
    o comment 23 and unregistered comment 1 are the same comment
    o comment 24 and unregistered comment 11 are the same comment
    o unregistered comments 8, 9 and 10 are the same comment (i.e. they
      are all part of the hash table proposal presented in comment 9).
 
  If you have any question, comment, objection to the classification
  below, let me know.
 
 
